  1. ([ISL] 4.11, 25 pt) In this problem, you will develop a model to predict whether a given car gets high or low gas mileage based on the Auto data set. Write a data analysis report addressing the following problems.

    1. Create a binary variable, mpg01, that contains a 1 if mpg contains a value above its median, and a 0 if mpg contains a value below its median.
library(ISLR) 
data("Auto") 
attach(Auto)
library(tidyverse)

Auto <- Auto %>%
  mutate (mpg01 = factor(ifelse(mpg > median(mpg), 1, 0)))

    1. Create subsets of the data for States New York, California, and Washington. Print out the dimension and first 6 observations of each state subset.

    2. Fit both cubic splines (using bs) and natural cubic splines (using ns) on each subset, with the number of cases as response, and the number of days since first case as predictor. Find the optimal degrees of freedom (df) for the basis.

    3. Generate a plot of three panels, each corresponding to one state. Each panel plots the observed data and the fitted splines (different colors for cubic spline and NCS). Compare and commment on the two types of splines.

    4. Use the fitted splines from Washington and California to predict the number of cases in New York State. Which prediction is better? Comment on why/why not the prediction is good.

    5. Now use Smoothing Spline (smooth.spline) to fit the California data, and predict its number of cases in the next 30 days. Plot the observed data, the fitted line, and its extrapolation in a single plot. Comment on the prediction you get.
